25. So much of the authority of the Example of pious men3 we have now to shew also that the Judyment of pious men is not a suffi- cient ground for the satisfaction of the conscience.

The arguments are nearly the same for this as for the other branch of the argument.

First, all men, however learned and pious, are liable to errour, as well as to sin: perhaps even more liable to errour than to sin, since it requires more acuteness to distinguish between truth and falsehood than between good and bad. Men err from Ignorance‚ Education‚ Custom, Perverse Affection, and many other causes.
